<P class="p10 ft9">DECRIPTION</P>
<P class="p11 ft10">For Information Management project, I have chosen to represent the various accommodation hostels of Trinity College. This model has various entities like Hostel Details, Student Details, Staff Details, Room Details, Complaint Details and Feedback Details.</P>
<P class="p12 ft10">For this database, there are numerous hostels, and for each hostel there are several students and rooms, and subsequently each hostel also employs several staff. For each room there can be multiple complaints and feedback on those complaints lodged.</P>
<P class="p7 ft10">The <NOBR>six-relation</NOBR> table that I have decided to model are listed as follows:</P>
<P class="p13 ft2"><SPAN class="ft2">1.</SPAN><SPAN class="ft11">Hostel Details</SPAN><SPAN class="ft10">:</SPAN></P>
<P class="p14 ft10"><SPAN class="ft12">•</SPAN><SPAN class="ft13">This table has all the essentials details for each individual Trinity accommodation.</SPAN></P>
<P class="p15 ft10"><SPAN class="ft12">•</SPAN><SPAN class="ft13">It has the following attributes:</SPAN></P>
<P class="p16 ft2">Hostel ID : Primary Key</P>
<P class="p17 ft10">Phone Number – Unique phone number of receptions for each hostel</P>
<P class="p18 ft10">Capacity – Total number of rooms for each hostel</P>
<P class="p18 ft10">Name – Unique name for each Trinity accommodation.</P>
<P class="p17 ft10">Address. – Street Name, City and State</P>
<P class="p19 ft10"><SPAN class="ft12">•</SPAN><SPAN class="ft13">Each hostel will have multiple students staying, employing multiple staff members.</SPAN></P>
<P class="p20 ft14"><SPAN class="ft2">2.</SPAN><SPAN class="ft11">Student Details</SPAN></P>
<P class="p21 ft10"><SPAN class="ft12">•</SPAN><SPAN class="ft13">This table contains the personal information for each student staying in the hostel accommodation.</SPAN></P>
<P class="p22 ft10"><SPAN class="ft12">•</SPAN><SPAN class="ft13">It has the following attributes:</SPAN></P>
<P class="p23 ft2">ID number: Primary Key</P>
<P class="p18 ft10">Name, Major, Year, Semester, Date of birth, Mobile, Email, Father's name,</P>
<P class="p23 ft10">Mother's name, Father's mobile number, Mother’s mobile number, Address</P>
<P class="p24 ft10"><SPAN class="ft12">•</SPAN><SPAN class="ft13">Each student has only 1 room and can have multiple complaints.</SPAN></P>
<P class="p13 ft14"><SPAN class="ft2">3.</SPAN><SPAN class="ft11">Staff Details</SPAN></P>
<P class="p25 ft10"><SPAN class="ft12">•</SPAN><SPAN class="ft13">This table contains the personal details for each staff member employed in a hostel.</SPAN></P>
<P class="p22 ft10"><SPAN class="ft12">•</SPAN><SPAN class="ft13">It has the following attributes:</SPAN></P>
<P class="p26 ft2">Staff ID number: Primary Key</P>
<P class="p23 ft10">Name, Role, Hostel ID, Mobile Number, Email, Address</P>
<P class="p22 ft10"><SPAN class="ft12">•</SPAN><SPAN class="ft13">Staff members will manage multiple complaints and will allot the rooms to the students.</SPAN></P>
<P class="p13 ft14"><SPAN class="ft2">4.</SPAN><SPAN class="ft11">Room Details</SPAN></P>
<P class="p25 ft10"><SPAN class="ft12">•</SPAN><SPAN class="ft13">This table contains the details for each room in a particular hostel.</SPAN></P>
<P class="p25 ft10"><SPAN class="ft12">•</SPAN><SPAN class="ft13">It has the following attributes:</SPAN></P>
<P class="p23 ft7">Hostel ID, Room Number, Block Number: Primary Key</P>
<P class="p23 ft10">Occupancy</P>
<P class="p22 ft10"><SPAN class="ft12">•</SPAN><SPAN class="ft13">Each room will have only one student allotted to it</SPAN></P>
<P class="p27 ft15">1</P>

<P class="p33 ft9">SECURITY CONSIDERATIONS</P>
<P class="p34 ft10">Security in a database is an important part when designing the database, the reason being that in an unsecure database, the data can be compromised and might even lead illegal privacy violations.</P>
<P class="p35 ft10">For the hostel management database, we plan to create different users having limited access which enables to fulfil only their particular set of duties. This ensures that privacy of users’ data is not compromised, and integrity of data is maintained by not giving extra privileges to users who don’t it.</P>
<P class="p31 ft10">The three roles that have been implemented in this database are as follows:</P>
<P class="p25 ft10"><SPAN class="ft10">1.</SPAN><SPAN class="ft16">Warden</SPAN></P>
<P class="p36 ft10"><SPAN class="ft10">2.</SPAN><SPAN class="ft16">Receptionist</SPAN></P>
<P class="p14 ft10"><SPAN class="ft10">3.</SPAN><SPAN class="ft16">Maintenance Staff</SPAN></P>
<P class="p13 ft17">For creating the above roles, the following commands were implemented:</P>
<P class="p36 ft10">1. Warden:</P>
<P class="p37 ft17">CREATE ROLE Warden;;</P>
<P class="p37 ft10">GRANT CREATE, DELETE ON student_details TO Warden;</P>
<P class="p38 ft10">GRANT UPDATE, SELECT ON student_details TO Warden WITH GRANT OPTION; GRANT CREATE, DELETE, UPDATE, READ ON Student_Room TO Warden WITH GRANT OPTION;</P>
<P class="p39 ft10">2. Receptionist:</P>
<P class="p37 ft10">CREATE ROLE Receptionist;</P>
<P class="p40 ft10">GRANT CREATE, SELECT, UPDATE ON Complaints TO Receptionist;</P>
<P class="p41 ft10">GRANT CREATE, DELETE, UPDATE, READ ON Student_Room TO Receptionist; GRANT UPDATE, READ ON Room_Info TO Receptionist;</P>
<P class="p42 ft10">3. Maintenance Staff:</P>
<P class="p43 ft10">CREATE ROLE MaintenanceStaff;</P>
<P class="p40 ft10">GRANT CREATE, SELECT, UPDATE ON Complaints TO MaintenanceStaff;</P>
<P class="p7 ft10">For assigning the above roles to the staff members we can use the following commands:</P>
<P class="p44 ft10">GRANT 'Warden' TO MollySatchz;</P>
<P class="p40 ft17">GRANT 'Receptionist' TO JimmySatchz</P>
<P class="p40 ft10">GRANT 'MaintenanceStaff' TO HannahBaker</P>
<P class="p7 ft10">For removing the privileges from staff members, the following command can be used:</P>
<P class="p28 ft17">:</P>
<P class="p40 ft10">REVOKE DELETE ON Room_Info FROM Receptionist;</P>
<P class="p45 ft10">Further, each user can be allotted a unique password key which automatically expires in a specific set of days:</P>
<P class="p46 ft10">CREATE USER 'HannahBaker' IDENTIFIED BY 'new_password' PASSWORD EXPIRE INTERVAL 180 DAYS;</P>
<P class="p47 ft15">6</P>

<P class="p48 ft9">SEMANTIC CONSTRAINTS</P>
<P class="p13 ft10"><SPAN class="ft10">1.</SPAN><SPAN class="ft18">Integrity constraints:</SPAN></P>
<P class="p49 ft10"><SPAN class="ft12">•</SPAN><SPAN class="ft13">All primary and foreign keys were declared as NOT NULL.</SPAN></P>
<P class="p50 ft10"><SPAN class="ft10">2.</SPAN><SPAN class="ft18">Semantic Constraints:</SPAN></P>
<P class="p9 ft10"><SPAN class="ft12">•</SPAN><SPAN class="ft13">Check Constraint:</SPAN></P>
<P class="p51 ft10"><SPAN class="ft19">o</SPAN><SPAN class="ft20">A check constraint is to limit the values that can be inserted in data variable.</SPAN></P>
<P class="p52 ft10"><SPAN class="ft10">▪</SPAN><SPAN class="ft13">For instance, CHECK (Capacity &gt; 0) would ensure that no hostel has capacity equal to or less than 0.</SPAN></P>
<P class="p53 ft10"><SPAN class="ft19">o</SPAN><SPAN class="ft20">A CHECK IN constraint is used to limit values from a set of </SPAN><NOBR>pre-defined</NOBR> values.</P>
<P class="p54 ft23"><SPAN class="ft10">▪</SPAN><SPAN class="ft21">For instance, CHECK </SPAN>(Rating <SPAN class="ft22">IN </SPAN>(1 , 2, 3, 4, 5)) would ensure that Rating can only take a value which lies in the set {1,2, 3, 4, 5}</P>
<P class="p55 ft9">VIEWS</P>
<P class="p56 ft10">The main function of Views is collection information from various different table which are used frequently. It is useful because it saves time without having to input the same query multiple times.</P>
<P class="p57 ft10">For this database, I have created a view wherein I am showing complaints which were resolved and the feedback that was obtained.</P>
<P class="p58 ft26"><IMG src="data:image/jpg;base64," id="p9inl_img1"><SPAN class="ft24"> 1. </SPAN><SPAN class="ft25">CREATE VIEW </SPAN>view_resolved_complaints <SPAN class="ft25">AS</SPAN></P>
<P class="p59 ft25"><IMG src="data:image/jpg;base64," id="p9inl_img2"><SPAN class="ft24"> 2. </SPAN>SELECT</P>
<P class="p59 ft26"><IMG src="data:image/jpg;base64," id="p9inl_img3"><SPAN class="ft24"> 3. </SPAN>complaints.complaint_ID,</P>
<P class="p59 ft27"><IMG src="data:image/jpg;base64," id="p9inl_img4"><SPAN class="ft24"> 4. </SPAN><SPAN class="ft26">complaints.category </SPAN><SPAN class="ft25">AS </SPAN>'Category of Complaint'<SPAN class="ft26">,</SPAN></P>
<P class="p59 ft26"><IMG src="data:image/jpg;base64," id="p9inl_img5"><SPAN class="ft24"> 5. </SPAN>complaints.complaint_date <SPAN class="ft25">AS </SPAN><SPAN class="ft27">'Complaint Date'</SPAN>,</P>
<P class="p25 ft31"><SPAN class="ft28">6. </SPAN>complaints.student_ID <SPAN class="ft29">AS </SPAN><SPAN class="ft30">'Student ID'</SPAN>,</P>
<P class="p60 ft26"><IMG src="data:image/jpg;base64," id="p9inl_img6"><SPAN class="ft24"> 7. </SPAN>student_room.room_no <SPAN class="ft25">AS </SPAN><SPAN class="ft27">'Room Number'</SPAN>,</P>
<P class="p59 ft26"><IMG src="data:image/jpg;base64," id="p9inl_img7"><SPAN class="ft24"> 8. </SPAN>feedback.rating <SPAN class="ft25">AS </SPAN><SPAN class="ft27">'Feedback Rating'</SPAN>,</P>
<P class="p59 ft27"><IMG src="data:image/jpg;base64," id="p9inl_img8"><SPAN class="ft24"> 9. </SPAN><SPAN class="ft26">feedback.comments </SPAN><SPAN class="ft25">AS </SPAN>'Feedback Comments'</P>
<P class="p59 ft24"><IMG src="data:image/jpg;base64," id="p9inl_img9"> 10. <SPAN class="ft25">FROM</SPAN></P>
<P class="p59 ft26"><IMG src="data:image/jpg;base64," id="p9inl_img10"><SPAN class="ft24"> 11. </SPAN>complaints,</P>
<P class="p59 ft26"><IMG src="data:image/jpg;base64," id="p9inl_img11"><SPAN class="ft24"> 12. </SPAN>student_room,</P>
<P class="p59 ft26"><IMG src="data:image/jpg;base64," id="p9inl_img12"><SPAN class="ft24"> 13. </SPAN>feedback</P>
<P class="p59 ft24"><IMG src="data:image/jpg;base64," id="p9inl_img13"> 14. <SPAN class="ft25">WHERE</SPAN></P>
<P class="p59 ft26"><IMG src="data:image/jpg;base64," id="p9inl_img14"><SPAN class="ft24"> 15. </SPAN>complaints.complaint_ID = feedback.complaint_ID</P>
<P class="p59 ft26"><IMG src="data:image/jpg;base64," id="p9inl_img15"><SPAN class="ft24"> 16.</SPAN><SPAN style="padding-left:83px;"><SPAN class="ft32">AND </SPAN>complaints.student_ID = student_room.student_ID;</SPAN></P>

<P class="p86 ft9">TRIGGERS</P>
<P class="p87 ft44">A trigger is set of SQL queries which are automatically executes when there is some operation performed on a table. The three operations on which triggers can be executed are DELETE, INSERT, and UPDATE.</P>
<P class="p88 ft10">All the triggers definitions along with SQL commands have been implemented in Appendix 3.</P>
<P class="p89 ft9">ADVANCED & ADDITIONAL FEATUES</P>
<P class="p90 ft45">1. Emergency Contact Listing</P>
<P class="p91 ft10">Emergency Contact Listing is crucial for every organization, yet it just so happens that it is overlooked and most of the time not given enough importance. It might happen that a particular student living in a hostel is in medical emergency or might go missing.</P>
<P class="p92 ft10">To address this issue, I have designed using a special curated procedure in SQL, which uses cursor to parse through the entire student detail table.</P>
<P class="p7 ft10">It basically returns just names and contact information for a student’s parents.</P>
<P class="p7 ft10">The SQL query for this part is attached in Appendix 5.1.</P>
<P class="p6 ft45">2. Auto Scheduler Back Up Data</P>
<P class="p93 ft10">It might happen that particular data entry has been accidentally deleted by the user or it might happen that the user needs access to some deleted data due to variety of reasons. This might include the office reception trying to contact student for payment of fine or some lost belonging which was found after the student left the hostel accommodation.</P>
<P class="p31 ft10">Hence, it would become easy for hostel administration to access this backup data.</P>
<P class="p94 ft10">To address this issue, I have created temporary table and a trigger which stores the data values deleted from student_details into delete_backup table.</P>
<P class="p95 ft10">And to make that those data values don’t stay in the database for forever, I have created an event which checks every for data entries which are older than 30 days and deletes them automatically, thus ensuring free space.</P>
<P class="p31 ft10">The SQL query for this part is attached in Appendix 5.2</P>
